<STARTDOC>
macro(id(name))
    (In html, defines tt(name) as the em(inline CSS id-tag) of the next html
tag. E.g, to set id tt(thisID) to the next section 
use tt(id(thisID)sect(Section name)), resulting in
the html markup+nl()
    tt(<h1 id="thisID">Section name</h1>).nl()
    When using tt(id(name)) the document's CSS should contain a tt(#name)
entry (so, for the example it should be a tt(#thisID) entry). Such an entry
can be specified in an em(internal style sheet). E.g., 
the tt(htmlstyle) macro can be used like this:nl()
    tt(htmlstyle(#thisID {color: blue;})) or in an em(external style sheet)
(configured using the tt(htmlstylesheet) macro).nl()
    This macro is only effective with html conversions, and only the last 
tt(id) macro specification of a series is used (e.g.,
tt(id(x)id(y)sect(z)) ignores tt(x), and adds tt(id="y") to
tt(sect(z))). 

 The tt(id) macro is supported by the following macros: tt(bf cell cells
center chapter code dit em figure file itdesc lchapter link lref lsect
lsubsect lsubsubsect nchapter npart nsect nsubsect nsubsubsect paragraph part
quote row sc sect strong subs subsect subsubsect subsubsubsect sups tt url
verb verbinclude).
 )
<>

DEFINEMACRO(id)(1)(\
<html>
    SETSYMBOL(XXid)(NOTRANS( id="ARG1"))\
<>
)

